Structure of the dataset and the feature of interest¶

The dataset contains 636 columns and 485490 row entries. Each row represents a student performance entry. The student performances are splitted into 3 main categories: Mathematics (PV1MATH to PV5MATH), Reading (PV1READ to PV5READ) and Science (PV1SCIE to PV5SCIE). All these columns are numeric but have data type object. I'll change the datatype of the columns during the analysis when needed.

Besides the performance variables, the dataset consists of various other variables such as living country, parent qualifications, possessions, subjective norms, experiences and many more.

Due to the large amount of data, this analysis will only concentrate on certain variables. For this purpose, I will create a new subset with the data of interest.

The main performance variable will be mathematics. I will try to find the features what best predict a mathematic performance above average.
The other features will be:

  • gender (ST04Q01)
  • immigration status (IMMIG)
  • attributions to failure in mathematics (FAILMAT)
  • mathematics anxiety (ANXMAT)
  • subjective norms in mathematics (SUBNORM)
  • instrumental motivation for mathematics (INSTMOT)
  • mathematics interest (INTMAT)
  • home educational resources (HEDRES)
  • out of school lessons in mathematics (ST55Q02)
  • Students responses regarding parental education ('MISCED' & 'FISCED')
  • How many books at home (ST28Q01)

Extracts from the PISA 2012 Technical Report are used to decribe these variables in more detail2.

Univariate Exploration¶

Main feature of interest: mathematic performance¶

PISA reports student performance through plausible values.
It has been noted that1:

The simplest way to describe plausible values is to say that plausible values are a representation of the range of abilities that a student might reasonably have. [] Instead of directly estimating a students ability $\theta$ , a probability distribution for a students $\theta$ is estimated. That is, instead of obtaining a point estimate for $\theta$ , like a WLE, a range of possible values for a students $\theta$ , with an associated probability for each of these values is estimated. Plausible values are random draws from this (estimated) distribution for a students $\theta$ (Wu and Adams, 2002).

The probability distribution for a students $\theta$ can be based on the cognitive data only, i.e. the item response pattern, but can also include additional information, such as student gender, social background, and so on. The probability distribution becomes therefore conditioned by this additional information. (OECD, 2002c).

Let's compare all 5 mathematic performances.
As almost all columns have as a datatype string, I create a function for changing datatypes to float when needed:

# function to add percentages into the plotbars
n_points = pisa.shape[0]
def pct_labels(col):
    cat_counts = pisa[col].value_counts()
    locs, labels = plt.xticks()
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        count=cat_counts[label.get_text()]
        pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_points)
        plt.text(loc, count-(count/100*50), pct_string, ha='center')
In [11]:

Attributions to failure in mathematics (FAILMAT)¶

Information from Pisa 2012 Technical Report:¶

A new scale indicating attributions to failure in mathematics (FAILMAT) was developed in PISA 2012 based on six items. Table 16.15 of the pisa technical report2 shows the item wording and the international item parameters for this scale. The response categories were Very likely, Likely, Slightly likely, Not at all likely. All items were reversed, so the higher difficulty corresponds to the higher level of external attribution of failure such as bad luck, bad guesses or the teacher.

Question:
Suppose that you are a student in the following situation: Each week, your mathematics teacher gives a short quiz. Recently you have done badly on these quizzes. Today you are trying to figure out why. How likely are you to have these thoughts or feelings in this situation?
ST44Q01 a) Im not very good at solving mathematics problems
ST44Q03 b) My teacher did not explain the concepts well this week
ST44Q04 c) This week I made bad guesses on the quiz
ST44Q05 d) Sometimes the course material is too hard
ST44Q07 e) The teacher did not get students interested in the material
ST44Q08 f) Sometimes I am just unlucky

Items were coded as (1=0), (2=1), (3=2), (4=3). Total score was calculated as a ratio of a sum of all questions over maximum score of valid responses (questions with missing value did not contribute to max score)

Mathematics Anxiety (ANXMAT)¶

Information from Pisa 2012 Technical Report:¶

Table 16.13 item parameters for mathematics anxiety (ANXMAT):
The five items measuring mathematics anxiety (ANXMAT) that were used in the Main Survey of PISA 2012 had also been used in PISA 2003. Table 16.13 shows the item wording and the international item parameters for this scale. The response categories were strongly agree, agree, disagree and strongly disagree. All items were reversed, so the higher difficulty corresponds to the higher level of anxiety.

Thinking about studying mathematics: to what extent do you agree with the following statements?
ST42Q01 a) I often worry that it will be difficult for me in mathematics classes
ST42Q03 c) I get very tense when I have to do mathematics homework
ST42Q05 e) I get very nervous doing mathematics problems
ST42Q08 h) I feel helpless when doing a mathematics problem
ST42Q10 j) I worry that I will get poor in mathematics

Items were reversely recoded as (4=0), (3=1), (2=2), (1=3).Total score was calculated as a ratio of a sum of all questions over maximum score of valid responses (questions with missing value did not contribute to max score).

It's interesting to see, that anxiety is based more on worry than on tensity, nervosity or even helpless feelings.

Subjective Norms in Mathematics (SUBNORM)¶

Information from Pisa 2012 Technical Report:¶

Table 16.11 item parameters for subjective norms in mathematics (SUBNORM):
A new scale was created in PISA 2012 consisting of six items measuring subjective norms in mathematics (SUBNORM) in the Main Survey. Table 16.11 shows the item wording and the international item parameters for this scale. The response categories range from Strongly agree, Agree, Disagree to Strongly disagree. All items were reversed, so the higher difficulty corresponds to the higher level of agreement. Values for delta indicated that students found it harder to agree with the statement My friends enjoy taking mathematics tests (d = 1.36) whereas it was relatively easy to agree with the statement My parents believe its important for me to study mathematics (d = -1.08).

Thinking about how people important to you view mathematics: how strongly do you agree with the following statements?
ST35Q01 a) Most of my friends do well in mathematics
ST35Q02 b ) Most of my friends work hard at mathematics
ST35Q03 c) My friends enjoy taking mathematics tests
ST35Q04 d) My parents believe its important for me to study mathematics
ST35Q05 e) My parents believe that mathematics is important for my career
ST35Q06 f) My parents like mathematics

Items were reversely recoded as (4=0), (3=1), (2=2), (1=3).Total score was calculated as a ratio of a sum of all questions over maximum score of valid responses (questions with missing value did not contribute to max score)

Item parameters for mathematics interest (INTMAT)¶

Information from Pisa 2012 Technical Report:¶

Table 16.9 item parameters for mathematics interest (INTMAT):
Four items measuring mathematics interest (INTMAT) were used in the Main Survey of PISA 2012 as well as for PISA 2003. Table 16.9 shows the item wording and the international item parameters for this scale. The response categories were Strongly agree, Agree, Disagree and Strongly disagree. All items were reversed so that the higher difficulty corresponds to a higher level of interest. For this index, item difficulties vary from a comparatively easy one I am interested in the things I learn in mathematics (d = -0.87) to a more difficult I enjoy reading about mathematics (d = 0.52). This indicates that even those students who are interested in the things they learn in mathematics do not necessarily read about mathematics.

# function to add percentages into the plotbars (y-axis)
def pct_labels_y(col):
    cat_counts = pisa[col].value_counts()
    locs, labels = plt.yticks()
    for loc, label in zip(locs, labels):
        count=cat_counts[label.get_text()]
        pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_points)
        plt.text(count+1000, loc, pct_string)

Students’ responses regarding parental education (MISCED & FISCED)¶

Information from Pisa 2012 Technical Report:¶

Students responses regarding parental education were classified using ISCED (OECD, 1999). Indices on parental education were constructed by recoding educational qualifications into the following categories: (0) None, (1) ISCED 1 (primary education), (2) ISCED 2 (lower secondary), (3) ISCED Level 3B or 3C (vocational/pre-vocational upper secondary), (4) ISCED 3A (general upper secondary) and/or ISCED 4 (non-tertiary post-secondary), (5) ISCED 5B (vocational tertiary) and (6) ISCED 5A, 6 (theoretically oriented tertiary and post-graduate). Indices with these categories were provided for the students mother (MISCED) and the students father (FISCED).

Conclusion of the univariate exploration¶

We observed a number of variables, a large majority of which are quantitative. The particular feature of these quantitative variables is that they can be broken down into categorical variables.
Most of the datatypes were changed, either as float for quantitative variables or categorical for the qualitative variables.
All nan values have been excluded from the analysis.

Conclusion of the bivariate exploration¶

Our bivariate exploration observed mainly two variables: mathematics scores and mathematics anxiety. It turned out that mathematics anxiety has a rather strong negative relationship to mathematics scores, so we observed the relationship of the anxiety with the other variables:

  • Female students seem more anxious than male students
  • The immigration status does not relate to the anxiety
  • Extracurricular mathematics hours do not reduce mathematics anxiety
  • The level of parental education seems to be related to mathematics anxiety: the higher the level of education, the lower the anxiety
  • The student's anxiety seems to be higher when the student's friends have a positive attitude toward mathematics.

The other part of our bivariate exploration was observing the relationship of the main variable mathematics scores with other variables:

  • Educational resources at home, like a desk or a quiet place to study, have a rather strong relationship with mathematics scores. The higher the level of education of the parents, the more educational resources at home available.
  • Gender and immigration status have no relationship with mathematics scores
  • The extracurricular mathematics hours do not relate to better mathematics scores
  • The level of parental education seems to be related to mathematics scores: the higher the educational level, the better the mathematics scores
  • The number of books at home have a relationship to the mathematics scores: the more books, the better the scores. Another visualization, comparing the number of books at home and the level of parental education, showed us that the highest level of education has the largest number of books at home.

It turned out that the variables interest in mathematics (INSTMAT), subjective norms in mathematics (SUBNORM) and instrumental motivation for mathematics (INSTMOT) have all strong relationship to one another. But since we are only interested in gaining insights into mathematics scores, we have excluded these 3 variables from our analysis.

Conclusion of the multivariate exploration¶

There is a relationship between the educational level of the parents, the number of books at home, the educational resources at home, the mathematics scores and the mathematics anxiety.
As we have already seen, mathematics anxiety and mathematics scores are closely related. It's difficult to find out which variable has the strongest influence on the other: do low mathematics scores increase mathematics anxiety? Or are the mathematics scores lower because of an unfounded mathematics anxiety, perhaps even adopted by friends of the student (SUBNORM)? Unfortunately we have not found a clear insight into this dilemma.
We have seen that the mathematics anxiety is lower when the parents have a higher educational level. These parents seem to provide more educational resources and to own more books at home. These combinations seem to have an impact on both the mathematics scores and the mathematics anxiety. Interestingly, we found out that even if the parents have a high level of education, if the number of books at home decreases, the mathemtics anxiety increases. On the other hand, if the parents have a low level of education, a high number of books does not relate to a lower level of anxiety or a better mathematics score.
So it seems that only both features number of books at home and high level of education combined could lead to better mathematics scores.
